WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.480
This next speaker is a repeat, and we always like to ask speakers a little fun fact about

00:00:06.480 --> 00:00:07.480
themselves.

00:00:07.480 --> 00:00:10.960
And his fun fact is, he ran out of fun facts.

00:00:10.960 --> 00:00:12.720
So with that, everyone please welcome Emil.

00:00:12.720 --> 00:00:13.720
Emil Hvitfeldt – Slidecraft, Quarto, revealjs, tidymodels

00:00:13.720 --> 00:00:14.720
I'm very happy to be here.

00:00:14.720 --> 00:00:18.280
This is a talk I've been very excited to talk about.

00:00:18.280 --> 00:00:23.959
I like to think about this topic as what I do when I'm supposed to do other things.

00:00:23.959 --> 00:00:28.320
So I'm sure some people in here wouldn't want to hear that.

00:00:28.320 --> 00:00:37.320
So while we wait for this to work, I'm going to give some disclaimers.

00:00:37.320 --> 00:00:42.680
When you spend time working on making your slides prettier for some definition of prettier,

00:00:42.680 --> 00:00:45.759
it can end up taking all the time you have.

00:00:45.759 --> 00:00:53.919
So my rule of thumb is, I set a predefined time of fixing the aesthetic of a slide, and

00:00:53.919 --> 00:00:57.480
then when I'm done with that, I don't spend more time on it.

00:00:57.639 --> 00:01:02.680
So if I have two days, I do one day of making them pretty, and then one day of filling in

00:01:02.680 --> 00:01:04.599
the content.

00:01:04.599 --> 00:01:09.480
So then you just use it, and it's the content switching kind of thing.

00:01:09.480 --> 00:01:13.400
I'm also not trying to pretend like I know anything about how to make things pretty,

00:01:13.400 --> 00:01:19.080
but I know how to change the aesthetic of slides in Quarto, and that's what I'll show

00:01:19.080 --> 00:01:20.080
now.

00:01:20.080 --> 00:01:22.879
I don't try to at all say I know what I'm doing.

00:01:22.879 --> 00:01:27.080
All right, let's try again one more time.

00:01:27.080 --> 00:01:32.599
So I'll be talking about what I like to call slide crafting, which is doing fun things

00:01:32.599 --> 00:01:33.599
with slides.

00:01:33.599 --> 00:01:38.519
All right, so before we need to talk about what is Quarto.

00:01:38.519 --> 00:01:46.120
So Quarto is this new open source scientific and technical publishing system built in PaintDot.

00:01:46.120 --> 00:01:51.559
It is this new thing from Parsif, I think last year we announced it.

00:01:51.559 --> 00:01:57.040
And everybody here, I assume, know or have heard about R Markdown.

00:01:57.040 --> 00:02:04.879
And Quarto is, I like to think of the technical, like the spiritual successor to R Markdown,

00:02:04.879 --> 00:02:12.360
except that now it works independent from R, so you also have support for Python, Julia,

00:02:12.360 --> 00:02:15.360
Observable, and it has room to improve later.

00:02:15.360 --> 00:02:21.479
It's built on PaintDot, Lua, so you don't need R installed anymore.

00:02:22.399 --> 00:02:24.279
But if you want to, you can use it with R.

00:02:24.279 --> 00:02:31.000
And yeah, it's like many, many years of R Markdown development has been distilled into

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:36.559
Quarto, so they learned from their mistakes and now everything fits more uniformly into

00:02:36.559 --> 00:02:38.720
one package.

00:02:38.720 --> 00:02:41.639
And it works the same, like the way you would expect.

00:02:41.639 --> 00:02:45.880
So here we have like a, you can use it with Jupyter Notebooks to do Python things, you

00:02:45.880 --> 00:02:49.360
can use it how you would R Markdown.

00:02:49.360 --> 00:02:53.119
It's a little bit different syntax-wise, but it's mostly the same.

00:02:53.119 --> 00:02:56.960
You can also use Julia or Observable.

00:02:56.960 --> 00:03:03.639
So, and I assume that our scripting languages will get support in the future.

00:03:03.639 --> 00:03:07.960
So if you're already familiar with R Markdown, I won't talk about it, Dan will talk a little

00:03:07.960 --> 00:03:12.520
bit about Quarto, so I won't go into any of the details.

00:03:12.520 --> 00:03:21.240
What I will talk about is one of the formats that come out of Quarto is this Reveal.js.

00:03:21.240 --> 00:03:28.000
So this is a framework of creating presentations and slides that are HTML slides.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:37.039
And these types of slides are reminiscent of like the Syringean, like Remot.js slides

00:03:37.039 --> 00:03:38.759
that we used to make.

00:03:38.759 --> 00:03:43.399
So there's some subtle differences on syntax and how actually everything works, but it's

00:03:43.399 --> 00:03:44.399
the same idea.

00:03:44.399 --> 00:03:49.360
You create basically a website, and this is what I'm using right now.

00:03:49.360 --> 00:03:52.160
So it looks like how we have up here.

00:03:52.160 --> 00:03:59.679
We have on the left, we have, yes, left, left we have a Quarto document, which is a glorified

00:03:59.679 --> 00:04:00.679
Markdown document.

00:04:00.679 --> 00:04:08.559
So we have a YAML at the top with some information, and then we do like headers to differentiate

00:04:08.559 --> 00:04:09.559
the slides.

00:04:09.559 --> 00:04:16.000
So level two header, which is like two hashtags, is a new slide.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:19.399
One is a section, so I tend to use the two.

00:04:19.399 --> 00:04:26.339
So we have like a title, and then each slide just works how you would expect with Markdown.

00:04:26.339 --> 00:04:33.200
So like bullet, like you can do like the little like, you can bold things how you expect them

00:04:33.200 --> 00:04:34.200
to bold.

00:04:34.200 --> 00:04:36.920
You can create lists the same way you do too.

00:04:36.920 --> 00:04:45.239
And how we expect from a Markdown, if you add total chunks, the total will be evaluated

00:04:45.239 --> 00:04:47.760
and be posted into the slides right away.

00:04:47.760 --> 00:04:55.559
So that's everything I'll be talking about how Reveal.js works in Quarto, just the basics.

00:04:55.559 --> 00:04:59.279
They have a great intro page of all the functionality.

00:04:59.279 --> 00:05:03.600
And I'm just going to point out some of the things that I tend to need and some of the

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:06.239
things that aren't documented.

00:05:06.239 --> 00:05:08.920
So we have net tolems.

00:05:08.920 --> 00:05:14.119
So we have these, they are like fenced diffs.

00:05:14.119 --> 00:05:22.640
So when you add these like triple tolems, they create a diff in HTML.

00:05:22.640 --> 00:05:28.279
And if you add like a thing after, like here's its tolems, so that will get a class tolems.

00:05:28.279 --> 00:05:29.559
And then you can nest them how you want.

00:05:29.559 --> 00:05:36.720
So here we have a bit old diff, tall tolems, and inside that we have two diffs, each with

00:05:36.720 --> 00:05:42.239
the class tolem, and they have their width set to 50%, so you get 50-50 tolems.

00:05:42.239 --> 00:05:48.679
And you can do whatever, this is flexible, you can add four tolems that all has width

00:05:48.679 --> 00:05:54.200
that add up to 100, or less than 100, so you have spaces and stuff.

00:05:54.200 --> 00:05:59.040
You can add images like absolute.

00:05:59.040 --> 00:06:03.880
So you put in an image like how you normally would, and then add the class absolute, and

00:06:03.880 --> 00:06:11.440
then with like top left, right, all these things and sizes, you can precisely put in

00:06:11.440 --> 00:06:17.799
an image where you want it to be, you don't have to try to make things work.

00:06:17.799 --> 00:06:26.320
One thing that isn't documented at all is if you diff a whole slide, the class center,

00:06:26.320 --> 00:06:33.600
it will center the content vertically, which is normally super hard to do, but you have

00:06:33.600 --> 00:06:39.760
like this little thing that centers it vertically, and it's really like, I think it's hard to

00:06:39.760 --> 00:06:42.200
use otherwise.

00:06:42.200 --> 00:06:47.799
And then another thing is if you just want the biggest text possible, you use the class

00:06:47.799 --> 00:06:55.519
R dash fit text, and it will just make it as big as it can within the container.

00:06:55.519 --> 00:07:02.000
So that is also very fast, which just makes slides all fit text everywhere, and you get

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:03.000
nice big slides.

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:04.000
All right.

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:07.559
So that's just like the basics, a little bit of how to do different things, there's a lot

00:07:07.559 --> 00:07:09.760
more information on the website.

00:07:09.760 --> 00:07:15.399
So the first thing when I want to change the state of my slides is I want to deal with

00:07:15.399 --> 00:07:17.279
colors and fonts.

00:07:17.279 --> 00:07:22.760
And I'm quite basic, so I end up on Pinterest, and you can just search color palettes, and

00:07:22.760 --> 00:07:25.880
a bunch of things come up, and it's all different.

00:07:25.880 --> 00:07:31.359
You can search beach theme, and it's all beach pictures with little palettes on them.

00:07:31.359 --> 00:07:33.239
But you can find your colors everywhere.

00:07:33.239 --> 00:07:37.040
You might have some inspiration, you have some pictures, you have something that inspires

00:07:37.040 --> 00:07:41.959
you, you use the eyedropper tool and pick out a certain number of colors.

00:07:41.959 --> 00:07:48.320
You don't necessarily want to go too overboard, and you need, I feel like you need two to

00:07:48.320 --> 00:07:49.880
at most five colors.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:54.679
So you need a background color, you need a text color, and then you have a color of accents.

00:07:54.679 --> 00:08:00.480
You also need to make sure that these colors work well together.

00:08:00.480 --> 00:08:07.440
So you need to make sure you've got your background, and that your text is visible when people

00:08:07.440 --> 00:08:09.440
don't have your computer right there.

00:08:09.440 --> 00:08:14.279
So you just search, like, color type chatter, you can put in some colors, and it will tell

00:08:14.279 --> 00:08:21.079
you how legible is the text.

00:08:21.079 --> 00:08:25.720
And annoyingly, it also depends on font size, so you can't just use the best number, you

00:08:25.720 --> 00:08:32.359
need to also look, is this going to be body text or titles.

00:08:32.359 --> 00:08:35.559
And then for fonts, you can use any type of font you want.

00:08:35.559 --> 00:08:40.159
I end up using Doodle fonts a lot because you just use the little import statement,

00:08:40.159 --> 00:08:43.159
and I will show how to do that later.

00:08:43.159 --> 00:08:50.280
But you also use local files as fonts, you have a really fancy font, or a homemade font.

00:08:50.280 --> 00:08:55.719
I have a blog post that is linked at the end showing you how to use any font at all.

00:08:55.719 --> 00:08:57.400
So you can, like, do really fun things.

00:08:57.400 --> 00:09:01.000
So just finding fonts, also just Doodle fonts, like, Doodle fonts work together.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:06.400
I don't, I end up stealing other people's fonts because I don't know enough about pitting

00:09:06.400 --> 00:09:08.039
Doodle fonts.

00:09:08.640 --> 00:09:18.159
All right, so these basic characteristics of how your slide works are governed by these

00:09:18.159 --> 00:09:20.640
things called SAS variables.

00:09:20.640 --> 00:09:25.039
And I'll show how to set them in a moment, but at the documentation with the little link

00:09:25.039 --> 00:09:33.119
at the bottom of the slide, we have these variable names, and they are fairly, like,

00:09:33.119 --> 00:09:34.119
intuitive names.

00:09:34.200 --> 00:09:39.440
So a background color and a body color, and, like, the font families of, like, presentations

00:09:39.440 --> 00:09:40.440
and other things.

00:09:40.440 --> 00:09:44.919
So you find what you want to change, and then you set that variable.

00:09:44.919 --> 00:09:46.640
So we're showing that right here.

00:09:46.640 --> 00:09:57.880
So add your, in your mat-dom file, you specify in the YAML saying, hey, I want to add some

00:09:57.880 --> 00:09:58.880
CSS.

00:09:58.880 --> 00:10:02.679
And here we're technically using, like, a SAS, SCSS.

00:10:02.679 --> 00:10:10.599
So it's, like, a supercharged SCSS that allows us to do larger and, like, more easily variable

00:10:10.599 --> 00:10:12.280
passing.

00:10:12.280 --> 00:10:16.760
And then, yeah, so we have, again, our style slide will look like this.

00:10:16.760 --> 00:10:24.020
So here is the input statement that came in that we downloaded from Doodle.

00:10:24.020 --> 00:10:30.400
And then we just say, hey, I want the font family of the sans serif description text.

00:10:30.400 --> 00:10:37.039
So we want the presentation size, like, the text size of everything to be fairly big because

00:10:37.039 --> 00:10:39.400
otherwise you can't read it.

00:10:39.400 --> 00:10:43.080
And it needs to be, it's bigger than you think, like, you can't do 20.

00:10:43.080 --> 00:10:45.159
You need to do, like, a fairly big number.

00:10:45.159 --> 00:10:47.559
And it will depend on your font you choose.

00:10:47.559 --> 00:10:49.799
And we can say, oh, I also want to change the link color.

00:10:49.799 --> 00:10:53.320
So that is, you also want to change the link color.

00:10:53.320 --> 00:10:57.679
And some of these variables are used throughout.

00:10:57.679 --> 00:11:02.200
So you could say, and it does it already, like, you have the link color.

00:11:02.200 --> 00:11:05.559
And you can reuse this link color over here.

00:11:05.559 --> 00:11:08.719
And we want to make it 25% lighter.

00:11:08.719 --> 00:11:11.159
So there is this, like, hierarchy of light.

00:11:11.159 --> 00:11:15.820
So you can specify everything at the top, and everything just, like, flows through.

00:11:15.820 --> 00:11:17.440
So you see now it looks light.

00:11:17.440 --> 00:11:19.679
Let's take a different font.

00:11:19.679 --> 00:11:20.679
The link color is different.

00:11:20.679 --> 00:11:23.679
You can see the link color.

00:11:23.679 --> 00:11:27.799
And we can also, let's say, oh, if you change the background color, we now have a new background

00:11:27.799 --> 00:11:29.799
color of everything.

00:11:29.799 --> 00:11:31.159
All right.

00:11:31.159 --> 00:11:39.359
So the way I end up doing all my slides is at the very top of my CSS file.

00:11:39.359 --> 00:11:45.479
I write, I create a bunch of variables, and all theme, and then a color name.

00:11:45.479 --> 00:11:51.359
And then I just pick the colors I'm using, and then I can use those color names later.

00:11:52.039 --> 00:11:58.599
So each color or name is only really going to be used once, because if I decide this

00:11:58.599 --> 00:12:03.559
blue isn't really, like, giving what I need, you can change it once, and everything flows

00:12:03.559 --> 00:12:04.559
through.

00:12:04.559 --> 00:12:08.799
And here are some slides here where you can then, like, everything works.

00:12:08.799 --> 00:12:14.200
What I also do with my colors is I create these custom CSS classes at the very bottom.

00:12:14.200 --> 00:12:18.239
You see it has .blue, and it's the color is my theme blue.

00:12:18.239 --> 00:12:20.799
And then I use that in, like, my slides, so that if I want to do some highlighting

00:12:20.799 --> 00:12:25.559
that's other than bolding, and making things italic, I can just say, hey, make this word

00:12:25.559 --> 00:12:30.280
blue, or make this area teal, and it works.

00:12:30.280 --> 00:12:33.599
And this isn't necessarily, you can also, like, you can also make these custom classes

00:12:33.599 --> 00:12:34.960
to make things bold.

00:12:34.960 --> 00:12:41.599
You can make things a specific font color, fonts, like, style, if you want to have, like,

00:12:41.599 --> 00:12:44.960
a wavy font to, like, show something is starry or something.

00:12:44.960 --> 00:12:52.640
You can have, like, a starry tag, and it just, like, you can use it.

00:12:52.640 --> 00:12:57.840
This becomes very manual over time, and what I do if I really feel like I want to do something

00:12:57.840 --> 00:13:10.159
kind of neat is I spend my time in my CSS, and I write these, like, themes that are,

00:13:10.159 --> 00:13:12.440
like, slide specific.

00:13:12.440 --> 00:13:15.960
So I'm saying on this slide, I want the background to be this.

00:13:15.960 --> 00:13:19.719
I want it to have these font colors, I want it to have these font sizes.

00:13:19.719 --> 00:13:26.239
If you used a Syringe, and that's an inverse theme, where you just put inverse, and then

00:13:26.239 --> 00:13:29.960
instead of being white with black text, it's black with white text.

00:13:29.960 --> 00:13:33.000
But you can, like, expand that however you want.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:38.000
So a little bit how in PowerPoint you have, like, a template where you say, oh, I want

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:41.880
to now add a thing that has, like, text on one side and image on the other side.

00:13:41.880 --> 00:13:46.559
That's what I'm doing here in CSS.

00:13:46.559 --> 00:13:52.679
So then when I'm writing my slides, I don't really use much theming.

00:13:52.679 --> 00:13:58.559
When I write the slides, I just add the theme type I want for each of the slides.

00:13:58.559 --> 00:14:02.020
So you get, like, slides that look like this.

00:14:02.020 --> 00:14:06.239
So now, like, it just knows everything.

00:14:06.239 --> 00:14:07.239
This is the background.

00:14:07.239 --> 00:14:10.200
It's just the SVG that has a little animation in it.

00:14:10.200 --> 00:14:14.200
But you can also say, like, here, like, there's a bit old globe on the right-hand side.

00:14:14.200 --> 00:14:19.320
And the CSS knows that and is restricting the area where the text will happen.

00:14:19.320 --> 00:14:21.200
So you don't have to do it manually every time.

00:14:21.200 --> 00:14:25.679
You set everything up front, and then you just write your slides real fast.

00:14:25.679 --> 00:14:28.760
And a lot of these can also be made to, like, be re-shared.

00:14:28.760 --> 00:14:29.880
So, like, you create it once.

00:14:29.880 --> 00:14:34.739
You create your talk slide that has all the colors you need.

00:14:34.739 --> 00:14:37.119
It has, like, a different, like, type of slide.

00:14:37.119 --> 00:14:41.559
You write it once, and then you use that every time moving forward.

00:14:41.559 --> 00:14:42.559
All right.

00:14:42.559 --> 00:14:43.559
Another thing.

00:14:43.559 --> 00:14:47.679
Oh, this is going to be hard for me.

00:14:47.679 --> 00:14:54.400
So another thing that I don't like about real slides is the way the content is.

00:14:54.400 --> 00:14:59.239
So the background just fills the screen no matter the size of the screen.

00:14:59.359 --> 00:15:07.039
So if you put in an image in the background, and your presentation dimensions is different

00:15:07.039 --> 00:15:13.119
than your computer dimensions, it might overlap with text because the background isn't absolute.

00:15:13.119 --> 00:15:15.679
It's based on the dimensions of the slide.

00:15:15.679 --> 00:15:18.880
So I wrote this Tor extension.

00:15:18.880 --> 00:15:25.960
So this is, like, it's basically Reveal.js slides, but they behave how, like, Syringe

00:15:25.960 --> 00:15:27.880
and Deadware, like.

00:15:27.880 --> 00:15:32.320
The slide content is always fixed in space, and then it just adds, like, a background

00:15:32.320 --> 00:15:34.359
color on the side.

00:15:34.359 --> 00:15:38.479
And this makes it, like, really easy to do something where you want an image that always

00:15:38.479 --> 00:15:41.359
takes up half.

00:15:41.359 --> 00:15:48.159
So here, like, the text will always be, like, the same compared to the images.

00:15:48.159 --> 00:15:55.159
That is not something you can do in a normal Reveal.js slides because of the way positioning

00:15:55.159 --> 00:15:58.320
it, if it works.

00:15:58.320 --> 00:16:02.200
One thing to add a little bit of, like, pizzazz to your slides is this thing called fragments.

00:16:02.200 --> 00:16:08.280
So you're specifying what needs to happen, and these fragments happen one by one.

00:16:08.280 --> 00:16:10.320
So you say there's a fragment.

00:16:10.320 --> 00:16:12.039
It defaults to, like, fading in.

00:16:12.039 --> 00:16:17.200
So when we go forward, the text that says fade in fades in.

00:16:17.200 --> 00:16:19.280
Then the next one will be the next sort of thing.

00:16:19.280 --> 00:16:20.280
It says fade out.

00:16:20.280 --> 00:16:22.080
It will fade out.

00:16:22.080 --> 00:16:27.119
And the things that says highlight red will highlight red.

00:16:27.119 --> 00:16:29.400
But we can also create our own fragments.

00:16:29.400 --> 00:16:31.440
So it comes from, like, 20 different ones.

00:16:31.440 --> 00:16:33.359
But we might want to do something a little bit more fun.

00:16:33.359 --> 00:16:36.520
So this is, like, a template of how it works.

00:16:36.520 --> 00:16:40.919
So you just copy this in and change the blue part to the name of what you want to call

00:16:40.919 --> 00:16:42.679
your fragment.

00:16:42.679 --> 00:16:46.479
And then you fill in the blanks.

00:16:46.479 --> 00:16:52.760
So here in this specific one, I want to say it needs to just look normal to begin with.

00:16:52.760 --> 00:16:58.840
But then when it becomes visible, it needs to have a background color of orange.

00:16:58.840 --> 00:17:06.119
So this means that when you have a new slide that you can do, like, you're highlighting,

00:17:06.119 --> 00:17:10.319
which I feel like this is more highlighting than, like, changing the color.

00:17:10.319 --> 00:17:11.880
So we have, like, oh, we're highlighting things.

00:17:11.880 --> 00:17:15.199
It's a little bit neat.

00:17:15.199 --> 00:17:25.719
Where things become a little bit more fun, I think, is this is just a HTML page that

00:17:25.719 --> 00:17:27.119
does some fancy things.

00:17:27.119 --> 00:17:38.680
And right now in this page, it has a JavaScript object that is, like, what the slides are.

00:17:38.680 --> 00:17:44.400
So this, like, reveal object has a lot of information about the slide and is used to

00:17:44.400 --> 00:17:45.400
modify it.

00:17:45.400 --> 00:17:53.560
So if I go into the console and press reveal.left, it will go back a slide.

00:17:53.560 --> 00:17:54.760
Or I can, like, go forward a slide.

00:17:54.760 --> 00:17:59.119
I can get, like, how far I am on my slides and find out all this information about the

00:17:59.119 --> 00:18:00.119
slide.

00:18:00.119 --> 00:18:01.119
Or, like, do things about it.

00:18:01.119 --> 00:18:05.119
I can shuffle the slides, which is kind of fun.

00:18:05.119 --> 00:18:07.640
What it has is these event listeners.

00:18:07.640 --> 00:18:14.680
So every time, like, first one, every code that is inside this, like, parentheses that

00:18:14.680 --> 00:18:21.880
says slide changed is run every time a slide is changed.

00:18:21.880 --> 00:18:29.280
Or you can run some arbitrary JavaScript code every time the window is resized.

00:18:29.280 --> 00:18:32.880
So if there's some things you can't do, if you know enough JavaScript, you can do anything

00:18:32.880 --> 00:18:33.959
you want.

00:18:33.959 --> 00:18:36.880
As a trader, whenever a slide is changed.

00:18:37.119 --> 00:18:43.479
What I found that what I want to spend time moving forward working on is this idea of

00:18:43.479 --> 00:18:46.760
fragment shown and fragment hidden.

00:18:46.760 --> 00:18:56.199
So every time a fragment is shown, you can also call arbitrary JavaScript code.

00:18:56.199 --> 00:19:03.560
So that's actually what I've been doing to do the, whenever I press forward, the embedded

00:19:03.560 --> 00:19:06.000
slide that moves forward.

00:19:06.119 --> 00:19:17.880
So I added advanced slide fragment, and every time it goes forward, it uses some JavaScript

00:19:17.880 --> 00:19:22.599
to find the iframe and advance it.

00:19:22.599 --> 00:19:25.560
And it also works backwards, so I also have it moving backwards.

00:19:25.560 --> 00:19:31.939
So when I hide it, so if I go back and forth, the slides inside work with me.

00:19:31.939 --> 00:19:33.520
And you can do more fun things with this.

00:19:33.520 --> 00:19:40.319
This is maybe not the, it's a way of hiding things, but you can add trader custom animations

00:19:40.319 --> 00:19:41.319
in JavaScript.

00:19:41.319 --> 00:19:44.199
So when you click something, something unfolds.

00:19:44.199 --> 00:19:48.040
You can do a lot of things, you can change.

00:19:48.040 --> 00:19:53.479
Things that you might not be able to do with CSS, you can now do with JavaScript.

00:19:53.479 --> 00:19:58.760
So this is where life becomes really hard for someone like me, because I have a real

00:19:58.760 --> 00:20:02.880
job, and I can't spend my time just writing slides all the time.

00:20:02.880 --> 00:20:03.880
All right.

00:20:03.880 --> 00:20:07.119
So this is how, like, this is basically how it looked when I did the thing.

00:20:07.119 --> 00:20:11.680
I put in my iframe, and then I just add these advanced slides underneath.

00:20:11.680 --> 00:20:14.280
And then it goes forward, and that's how we advance everything.

00:20:14.280 --> 00:20:15.280
